        heading:'Structural — walls, floors, ceilings, stairs',
        body:`Walls and Ceilings (Low to Severe):\nWalls and ceilings must be structurally sound and free of hazardous conditions. Deficiency levels:\n• Minor cosmetic damage (small holes, scuffs, peeling paint in post-1978 unit): Low\n• Peeling paint in pre-1978 unit: Moderate + lead paint regulatory trigger\n• Large holes providing access to electrical or structural cavities: Moderate\n• Active water damage causing deterioration: Moderate to Severe\n• Structural compromise (sagging, cracking in load-bearing walls): Severe to Life-Threatening\n• Mold growth on walls or ceilings: Severe (can escalate to LT)\n\nFloors (Low to Severe):\n• Minor surface damage (scratches, small chips): Low\n• Soft, spongy, or water-damaged flooring: Moderate to Severe depending on extent\n• Flooring so deteriorated it creates a trip hazard: Moderate\n• Structural floor damage (visible deterioration of subfloor or joists): Severe\n\nInterior Stairs within Units (Moderate to Life-Threatening):\nStairs inside duplex or townhouse-style units are inspected as part of the unit.\n• Damaged or missing tread: Moderate to Severe\n• Missing handrail with evidence of prior installation: Life-Threatening\n• Handrail loose or not secured properly: Severe\n• Riser height inconsistent (tripping hazard): Moderate`
