        heading:'Safety devices, doors, and windows',
        body:`Smoke Detectors (Not Scored — 24 hr fix, marked *):\nRequired in every unit, typically in each bedroom and in hallways serving sleeping areas. Must be operable — test with test button or test spray. As of December 2024, battery-only detectors must have sealed tamper-proof batteries.\n\nCarbon Monoxide Alarms (Life-Threatening, Not Scored — 24 hr fix, marked +):\nRequired in units with gas appliances, oil-burning appliances, or attached garages. Must be installed in proper location per manufacturer specs — typically within 10 feet of each sleeping area. Missing = Life-Threatening.\n\nUnit Entry Door (Life-Threatening):\nSee Chapter 5 for full coverage. Must close, latch, and lock. Missing or non-functional entry door = Life-Threatening. Door frame must be intact.\n\nInterior Doors (Low):\nInterior doors within a unit (bedroom, bathroom, closet) are inspected for basic functionality. A bedroom door that cannot close for privacy is Low. An interior door with a severely damaged frame or missing entirely is Low to Moderate.\n\nWindows — Egress (Life-Threatening):\nBedroom windows on floors 1–3 must provide adequate egress — fully openable, correct minimum size. See Chapter 5 for full criteria.\n\nWindows — General (Low to Moderate):\n• Broken window glass: Moderate (security/safety/weatherization concern)\n• Window will not open or close (non-egress window): Low\n• Window lock non-functional: Low to Moderate depending on floor and security implications\n• Window screen missing or damaged: Low (in most cases)\n\nDoor Locks and Hardware (Low to Moderate):\nDeadbolts and door locks must be functional. A unit entry door with a non-functional deadbolt is Moderate. A door knob that doesn't latch is Low. Door viewers (peepholes) are Low if missing.`
